      <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="leaf" size={22} /></div><strong>COX-2 + LOX Dual Block (Ginger)</strong><p>Gingerols inhibit both COX-2 (prostaglandin pathway) and LOX (leukotriene pathway) — providing broader anti-inflammatory coverage than single-pathway NSAIDs. This complements curcumin's NF-kB mechanism for triple-pathway inflammatory suppression.</p></div>
      <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="flask" size={22} /></div><strong>Bioavailability Enhancement</strong><p>Standard curcumin has 1-2% bioavailability. BioPerine (piperine) increases absorption 2,000%. Meriva (phospholipids), CurcuWIN (water-dispersion), and Longvida (lipid-binding) offer alternative enhancement technologies. Absorption technology is essential.</p></div>
      <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="heart" size={22} /></div><strong>Digestive Synergy</strong><p>Ginger's prokinetic effects stimulate gastric motility, reduce nausea, and calm digestive discomfort. This prevents the GI side effects some users experience with turmeric while providing its own anti-inflammatory benefits in the digestive tract.</p></div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A meta-analysis of 8 RCTs published in the <em>Journal of Medicinal Food</em> found that <strong>curcumin supplementation significantly reduced CRP (C-reactive protein) levels — a primary biomarker of systemic inflammation</strong>. Multiple trials have found curcumin comparable to NSAIDs for osteoarthritis pain relief with fewer gastrointestinal side effects, positioning it as a natural anti-inflammatory alternative for chronic joint inflammation.</p>
      <cite>Sahebkar et al. — Journal of Medicinal Food (CRP Meta-Analysis)</cite>
    </div>

