    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Turmeric and Ginger Gummies</h2>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Why combine turmeric and ginger together?</summary><p>They block different inflammatory pathways. Turmeric (curcumin) inhibits NF-kB + COX-2. Ginger (gingerols) inhibits COX-2 + LOX. Together: NF-kB + COX-2 + LOX triple-pathway suppression. Ginger also prevents turmeric-related stomach discomfort.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How much turmeric and ginger should I take daily?</summary><p>Turmeric: 500-2,000mg extract (95% curcuminoids) with BioPerine or absorption technology. Ginger: 250-1,000mg extract. Without piperine or absorption tech, curcumin bioavailability is only 1-2% — most is wasted. Always check for absorption enhancement.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What are turmeric and ginger gummies good for?</summary><p>Joint inflammation/stiffness, exercise recovery (DOMS), digestive health, immune modulation, cardiovascular support (endothelial function), brain health (neuroinflammation). Most effective for chronic low-grade inflammation driving joint pain and aging.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Do turmeric gummies work without black pepper?</summary><p>Standard curcumin: only 1-2% absorbed without enhancement. BioPerine increases absorption 2,000%. Alternatives: Meriva (phospholipids), CurcuWIN (water-dispersion), Longvida (lipid-bound). Without some absorption technology, most curcumin is wasted.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Are there side effects from turmeric and ginger gummies?</summary><p>Generally well-tolerated. Possible: mild GI discomfort at high doses. Both have mild anticoagulant effects — consult doctor if on blood thinners. Avoid turmeric with gallbladder disease. Discontinue 2 weeks before surgery. BioPerine may affect drug metabolism.</p></details>

